WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:04.277
SPEAKER_00: A radiation machine gave one patient roughly 100 times the intended dose.

00:00:05.259 --> 00:00:07.343
SPEAKER_00: The manufacturer said it was impossible.

00:00:08.224 --> 00:00:09.105
SPEAKER_00: Then it happened again.

00:00:09.147 --> 00:00:14.555
SPEAKER_00: The Therac-25 replaced physical safety interlocks with software checks.

00:00:15.436 --> 00:00:24.132
SPEAKER_00: During fast data entry, a race condition could leave the machine in the wrong state and fire a full power beam with no filter.

00:00:24.111 --> 00:00:30.304
SPEAKER_00: Nobody caught it because the code had been reused from older machines, and reused code felt like tested code.

00:00:31.246 --> 00:00:32.710
SPEAKER_00: Operators reported errors.

00:00:33.610 --> 00:00:36.838
SPEAKER_00: The manufacturer insisted the machine was safe.

00:00:36.936 --> 00:00:40.146
SPEAKER_00: More patients were burned before the pattern was treated as real.

00:00:40.185 --> 00:00:43.215
SPEAKER_00: The disaster was not just bad code.

00:00:43.896 --> 00:00:51.459
SPEAKER_00: It was a system with no independent safety layer, no quick way to believe field reports, and no design for software being wrong.

00:00:52.601 --> 00:00:56.412
SPEAKER_00: That is how small causes become massive consequences.
